---
import CaseStudyLayout from '../../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro';

// CASE_STUDY_PLACEHOLDER — replace with real client details when approved

const data = {
  metaTitle: 'Document Management & Approval Workflow System — All Webbed Labs',
  metaDescription: 'How we helped a Queensland state government department replace email-based document approval and spreadsheet tracking with a digital workflow — cutting average approval time from 11 days to 2.5 days and FOI response time from 18 days to 4 days.',
  industry: 'Government',
  tags: ['React', 'Node.js', 'PostgreSQL', 'DocuSign API', 'Audit Logging'],
  title: 'Document Management & Approval Workflow System',
  summary: 'A Queensland state government department processing 2,400 documents per year for ministerial sign-off was running approval chains through email, tracking status in a shared spreadsheet, and still requiring physical signatures on some documents. FOI requests were a monthly excavation exercise. We replaced it with a digital workflow that halved approvals to 2.5 days and got FOI response time under a week.',
  heroImageDescription: 'Document dashboard showing the approval workflow pipeline with stage indicators, reviewer assignments and approval history alongside the DocuSign digital signature integration and audit trail panel',

  clientOverview: 'A Queensland state government department responsible for infrastructure planning approvals, with 180 staff across several functional areas including policy, assessment, legal, and administrative support. The department processes approximately 2,400 documents per year requiring multi-level review and, for the most significant decisions, ministerial sign-off. The approval hierarchy involves between three and seven reviewers depending on document type and significance.',
  clientSize: '180 staff, ~2,400 documents/year requiring approval',
  clientLocation: 'Brisbane, QLD',

  pullQuote: 'Before this system, answering a FOI request meant someone spending days finding, printing and redacting documents from emails and shared drives. Now I can generate the full document history for any approval in about four minutes.',
  pullQuoteAuthor: 'Director, Governance and Legal',
  pullQuoteRole: 'Queensland State Government Department',

  challenge: [
    'The department\'s approval process had evolved organically over many years, and the result was a system that was surprisingly fragile for an organisation making decisions with significant public consequence. Documents were created in Word, saved to a SharePoint directory, and then shared for review via email — with the document attached or a link provided depending on reviewer preference. The practical result was that multiple versions of significant documents existed simultaneously across individual staff email inboxes and shared drives, with no reliable mechanism for ensuring reviewers were commenting on the current version.',
    'The approval chain was tracked in a shared Excel spreadsheet maintained by two administrative staff. Each row represented a document. Columns indicated which reviewer had received it, whether they had responded, and whether their response was an approval, a request for changes, or an escalation. The spreadsheet was updated manually — staff would email the administrators to report their approval, and the administrators would update the sheet. When staff forgot to send the update email, or when emails were missed, the spreadsheet fell out of sync with reality. The administrative staff spent a significant portion of their day chasing approvers for status updates, a task that was both time-consuming and — in a department with senior executives — politically delicate.',
    'Physical signatures were still required for a subset of documents — specifically those requiring ministerial endorsement and those that formed part of formal statutory processes. The physical signature requirement meant documents had to be printed, physically transported (sometimes between floors, sometimes between buildings), signed, scanned, and filed. For time-sensitive approvals, this process created delays measured in days. During the COVID-19 pandemic, when staff were working from home, this process had essentially broken down and was managed through a combination of informal digital approvals that were not legally defensible and physical couriers to ministers\' residences, which was neither efficient nor appropriate as a permanent solution.',
    'The audit trail problem was the one that had the most direct legal consequence. Under the Right to Information Act 2009 (Qld), the department had obligations to produce documents responsive to RTI (Queensland\'s equivalent of FOI) requests within prescribed timeframes. Because approvals were tracked through email chains and a spreadsheet rather than in a structured system, producing the documentary record for any given approval decision required manual archaeology: searching individual email accounts, reconstructing the chronology from email timestamps, locating the correct version of the document from SharePoint\'s version history (when it was used correctly), and assembling the chain of approvals into a format that could be disclosed.',
    'The department received approximately three RTI requests per month that required this kind of reconstruction. Each one was taking an average of 18 days to respond to — against the Act\'s 25-business-day limit. The timeline was technically within the statutory limit, but it left no margin for complex requests, and the administrative load was described by the Director of Governance as "consuming the team." There had been two occasions in the previous two years where the department had needed to seek an extension from the Office of the Information Commissioner — a step that attracts scrutiny and implies inadequate document management practices.',
  ],

  whyUs: [
    'The department had been through a formal procurement process, which we entered as a responsive tender to an open market approach. Our submission was not the cheapest. It was selected because it was the only submission that specifically addressed the RTI compliance requirements as a primary design constraint rather than a feature, and because we proposed building the audit logging as a first-class system capability rather than an add-on.',
    'During the procurement assessment, the evaluation panel asked all shortlisted vendors a specific question: "How would your system produce a complete audit trail for a document that was approved 18 months ago, including all versions, all reviewer comments and all sign-off timestamps?" Our answer described a specific technical approach — append-only event logging with cryptographic timestamps, version storage in immutable S3 objects, and a report generator that could reconstruct the full documentary history for any document at any point in time. The panel\'s notes from the assessment, which we saw during the project kickoff, indicated this was the differentiating response.',
  ],

  approach: [
    'Government projects require a level of process discipline that differs from commercial projects, and we adjusted our approach accordingly. The project had a formal project sponsor (the Deputy Secretary), a project steering committee that met fortnightly, and a series of milestone approvals required before proceeding from each phase to the next. We treated this governance structure as a feature of the engagement rather than an overhead — the approval gates created structured points for confirming alignment before committing development resources.',
    'Discovery was conducted under an NDA and involved reviewing the department\'s current workflows in significant detail. We shadowed the administrative staff who managed the approval spreadsheet for two full days, following documents through their approval journey. We interviewed reviewers at different seniority levels to understand what information they needed at each stage and what friction in the current process most affected them. We reviewed a sample of 40 completed approval records to understand the variation in document types, approval chains and timelines.',
    'The RTI compliance requirement drove a specific architectural decision that we made early: the audit log would not be a feature of the workflow system — it would be the foundation it was built on. Every state change in a document\'s lifecycle would be recorded as an immutable event: document created, version uploaded, assigned to reviewer, comment added, approval given, returned for changes, escalated, signed, finalised. The workflow status visible to users would be derived from this event stream, not maintained as separate state. This meant the audit trail was not something that had to be "generated" — it was always there, as the complete and accurate history of every action taken.',
    'We engaged the department\'s legal team early to understand the specific requirements for documents submitted to ministerial sign-off. There were existing legal opinions about the validity of electronic signatures for different document categories — some documents could be digitally signed without qualification, others required specific authentication standards, and a small category required wet ink signatures by statute. We mapped every document type in the department\'s portfolio against this assessment and designed the workflow routing to enforce the correct signature method automatically rather than relying on staff knowing which rule applied to which document type.',
  ],

  solution: [
    'The platform is a React application backed by a Node.js API and PostgreSQL database, hosted on AWS in the Sydney region. Document storage uses S3 with versioning enabled and server-side encryption at rest. Every document version is stored immutably — once uploaded, a version cannot be modified or deleted by any user, including administrators. This is the technical guarantee that underpins the audit trail\'s reliability.',
    'Document creation begins with the author uploading a document and selecting its type from a department-maintained taxonomy. The document type determines the approval chain — which roles must review it, in what sequence, whether parallel review is permitted, whether ministerial sign-off is required, and what signature method applies. Authors cannot select an approval chain manually; the system derives it from the document type, removing a category of errors entirely.',
    'The approval workflow is a state machine. Each document is always in exactly one state: draft, in review (with the specific reviewer identified), returned for changes, escalated, pending signature, or finalised. Transitions between states are logged as events. Reviewers see their queue of documents awaiting action. When a document is returned for changes, the author receives a notification with the reviewer\'s comments attached. When a document is approved, it automatically moves to the next stage in the chain. When all approvals are complete, the document moves to the signature stage.',
    'DocuSign handles digital signatures for the documents that permit them. We integrated DocuSign\'s API to generate a signing request automatically when a document reaches the signature stage, routing to the appropriate signatory based on the document type and the pre-configured signature authority register. The signatory receives a DocuSign email, signs through the DocuSign interface, and the completion webhook updates the document\'s status in the platform to finalised. The signed PDF is stored in S3 alongside the original and all intermediate versions. For documents requiring wet ink signatures — a small residual category — the system generates a cover sheet for printing and tracks the physical signature through a manual confirmation step.',
    'The PDF stamping feature applies a visible approval record to the final version of every approved document — a footer or header showing the approval date, the approving officer\'s name and role, the unique document reference number, and a verification URL where the approval can be confirmed. This is important for documents that are subsequently shared outside the department, as the stamp provides evidence of approval status without requiring access to the internal system.',
    'Reporting and RTI response capability was built as a first-class feature. For any document, any authorised user can generate a complete documentary history report: all versions of the document with upload timestamps, all reviewer assignments and responses with timestamps, all comments, all escalations, the complete approval chain with decision dates, and the final signed version. This report is generated as a PDF that can be produced and disclosed without any manual compilation. The Director of Governance described reviewing this feature during user acceptance testing as "genuinely emotional — we\'ve never been able to produce this before."',
    'Role-based access control reflects the department\'s organisational hierarchy. Authors can create and edit documents in draft. Reviewers can access documents assigned to them. Senior officers can see all documents in their business unit. Administrators can see everything and manage the document type taxonomy and approval chain configurations. The system does not allow any user to access a document they are not authorised to see — which is essential for a department where different teams work on matters that may be commercially or legally sensitive relative to each other.',
  ],

  implementation: [
    'The project was implemented in three phases with formal gateway approvals between each. Phase 1 was the document management and workflow engine — creation, versioning, assignment and the approval state machine. Phase 2 was the DocuSign integration and PDF stamping. Phase 3 was the RTI report generation and the bulk migration of historical documents from SharePoint.',
    'The SharePoint migration was a significant exercise. The department\'s SharePoint environment contained approximately 12,000 documents accumulated over six years, in a folder structure that had been created organically and was not consistent with the new document taxonomy. We built a migration tool that the department\'s administrative staff used to classify existing documents and map them to the new system — a process that took four weeks and involved difficult decisions about how to handle documents that predated the new approval workflow. Historical documents were imported with their SharePoint version history where that existed, and with a single version where it did not.',
    'User acceptance testing was conducted with twelve staff members representing different roles and document types. We ran 85 scripted test scenarios covering the full range of workflow variations — standard two-step approvals, multi-level escalations, returns for revision, parallel review on large documents, ministerial sign-off processes, and RTI report generation. Seven scenarios identified issues requiring fixes before go-live. Two of these were significant: one related to how the system handled simultaneous edits by two authors on different sections of a multi-part document, and one related to a DocuSign timeout handling case that could result in a signing request appearing to succeed while actually failing.',
    'Go-live was a managed cutover. On the designated Monday morning, the shared Excel approval tracking spreadsheet was locked for editing by all users except the two administrators, who spent the first week completing the migration of any in-progress approvals — entering their current status into the new system rather than attempting to complete them in the old process. New documents from go-live day were processed exclusively through the new system. By the end of the first week, all 23 in-progress approvals had been migrated and the spreadsheet was retired.',
  ],

  lessonsLearned: [
    'The document type taxonomy — the classification system that determines the approval chain for each document — required considerably more consultation than we had budgeted. Our initial assumption was that the department would have a reasonably clear existing classification scheme that we could implement. In practice, document types had been defined inconsistently across different teams over time, and there were genuine disagreements among senior staff about whether certain documents belonged in the same category for approval purposes. We facilitated three working sessions with team leads to reach consensus before we could finalise the configuration. This kind of organisational alignment work is not typically scoped into a software project, and we should have flagged it as a risk earlier.',
    'The physical signature residual category — the small number of documents that legally required wet ink signatures — turned out to be a persistent source of process complexity disproportionate to its volume. Because these documents could not complete the digital workflow automatically, they required a manual intervention step that sat outside the system\'s state machine and created gaps in the audit trail. We implemented the manual confirmation step as a workaround, but it is not as clean as the fully digital path. The longer-term resolution is for the department to pursue a legislative or policy amendment that would allow electronic signatures for these categories — which is a departmental governance matter, not a technical one.',
    'We underestimated the training requirement for the reviewer cohort — specifically, senior executive reviewers who had previously been recipients of email-based document review requests and expected the new system to work the same way. Several executives initially did not engage with the notification emails the system was sending them, because they looked different from the ad hoc email requests they were used to. The solution was partly technical (redesigning the notification email template to be more explicitly actionable) and partly procedural (the project sponsor sending a direct communication to all executive reviewers setting expectations). The lesson is that user adoption for senior stakeholders in government environments often requires executive sponsorship, not just good system design.',
    'The audit log\'s append-only architecture — which we were confident was the right approach — created an unexpected challenge during user acceptance testing when a tester asked what happened if an event was recorded incorrectly. Because events are immutable, an incorrectly recorded event cannot be edited or deleted. The answer — that a correction event is recorded on top of the incorrect event, with both remaining visible — was technically correct and legally sound, but required more explanation than we had anticipated. We added explicit guidance to the system\'s help documentation about how corrections are handled, and the legal team reviewed and approved the approach before go-live.',
  ],

  whatCameNext: [
    'Following the successful Phase 3 completion, the department asked us to build an integration with the Queensland Government\'s central correspondence management system, which tracks ministerial correspondence and briefings. The integration allows documents approved through the departmental workflow to be registered automatically in the central system rather than requiring a manual registration step by the admin team.',
    'There is a roadmap item for AI-assisted document routing — using document content analysis to suggest the correct document type and approval chain rather than requiring the author to select it manually. This would address a recurring issue where authors misclassify documents, triggering the wrong approval chain. The audit log\'s event data provides a rich training dataset for this kind of classification model. We have scoped the technical approach and are waiting on the department\'s AI governance approval process to proceed.',
    'Two other Queensland government agencies have been in contact through whole-of-government channels, having seen the department\'s system demonstrated at an inter-agency best practice forum. We are currently in early discussions about whether a shared-platform approach would be appropriate, with agency-specific configuration for document taxonomies and approval chains. This would be a different commercial and technical model — multi-tenanted rather than single-agency — and would require careful consideration of data separation requirements.',
  ],

  resultsNarrative: 'The shift from 11 days to 2.5 days average approval time represents more than an efficiency gain — it represents a change in the department\'s operational rhythm. Decisions that previously sat in email inboxes for days are now visible, trackable and progressing. The RTI compliance picture has also transformed: the department has not needed to seek an extension from the Office of the Information Commissioner since go-live, and the Director of Governance has described the change in her team\'s workload as "like having a different job."',

  metrics: [
    { value: '2.5 days', label: 'Average document approval time', context: 'Down from 11 days; measured across all document types in the first 6 months of operation' },
    { value: '4 days', label: 'Average RTI response time', context: 'Down from 18 days average; well within the 25-business-day statutory limit under the Right to Information Act 2009 (Qld)' },
    { value: '0', label: 'Version conflicts since go-live', context: 'Completely eliminated; previously a recurring issue causing rework and approval delays' },
    { value: '100%', label: 'Digital signature adoption', context: 'For all document categories permitting electronic signature; achieved within 6 weeks of go-live' },
    { value: '71%', label: 'Reduction in approval chasing time', context: 'Staff time spent following up on approval status; two admin staff\'s primary daily activity largely eliminated' },
    { value: '100%', label: 'Audit trail completeness', context: 'Every approval action recorded with timestamp and actor; previously estimated at ~60% based on RTI response quality assessments' },
  ],

  techStack: [
    { name: 'React', reason: 'Complex role-based document workflow interface with real-time status updates and multi-level review queues' },
    { name: 'Node.js', reason: 'API layer, event processing pipeline, and background jobs for notification dispatch and document stamping' },
    { name: 'PostgreSQL', reason: 'Relational structure for the approval workflow state machine, user roles and document metadata' },
    { name: 'AWS (EC2 + RDS + S3)', reason: 'Sydney-region hosting; S3 with versioning enabled for immutable document version storage; encryption at rest' },
    { name: 'DocuSign API', reason: 'Electronic signature workflow for ministerial and executive approvals requiring legally compliant digital signatures' },
    { name: 'Append-only Event Log', reason: 'Immutable audit trail architecture — every state change recorded as a permanent event; foundation for RTI report generation' },
    { name: 'PDF Stamping Pipeline', reason: 'Automated approval record stamping on finalised documents, applied on workflow completion' },
    { name: 'Role-Based Access Control', reason: 'Granular access control aligned to departmental hierarchy; enforced at API and storage layer' },
  ],

  relatedCaseStudies: [
    {
